It’s o-fish-al FinFam!! Rebranding and taking a new direction with my main mersona. Maui has always been #theabalonemerman. But I’m now focusing more on just that side and dropping Maui altogether.

It’s been a long time coming and aside from the occasional Bahari, I’ve wanted to switch it up. Keenon the Abalone Merman is here to stay, and the mersona who everyone will meet at performance events. Thank you all for this incredible journey with Merman Maui, and I’m so excited for this new chapter! 💚💙💚

It’s moments like this where I can acknowledge how far I’ve come. That little insecure kid who was afraid of the world, and afraid to have a voice. We’ve grown so much! And who knew we’d really settle into this directors chair, aaaaand that it would bring me back to @pcpatheatre 

To think that I… me… could be standing here right now, opening this beautiful show with the most amazing team.  It still doesn’t feel quite real.

And the way my designers were able to manifest this beautiful art piece of a set based off my visions is otherworldly. 

@jbo_1.0 this set is a dream, @zlightdesign these lights are pure magic (and thanks for these videos!), @jackdmyles my right hand and keeping me on track and trusting me, and so many more that made this a reality. I’m in debt to you all, for manifesting this guys dreams in such a special way.

Happy opening my loves, and thank you for helping me bring this community some holiday magic this year. 💚💚💚

I’ve both lost and found myself over and over again. But finally I think this is it. I’ve never felt this feeling before, that feeling of truly loving yourself completely and whole heartedly. And you know what? It really is beautiful 🥹💚

Life really is short friends, so why not just enjoy it? 😘

Habari Gani?! (What’s the News?) 

Umoja! (Unity)

Joyous Kwanzaa everyone! It’s truly one of my favorite times of year. I leave it refreshed and rejuvenated, and ready to tackle the year to come! What exactly is Kwanzaa you ask? Is it a religious holiday? To that I say no. Kwanzaa is a seven day African American celebration of life, culture, and heritage. We use this time to look back on our ancestral history, while acknowledging ways in which we can better ourselves and our community. In doing so, we stem those ideas around seven principles in which we honor each day. 

Today is Umoja, which means Unity. As we work to repair a divided worl, we as a whole need Umoja more than ever. How can you find Umoja within yourself today? You are already taking part just by being here and willing to learn. For how can we unify if we don’t understand each other? Thank you from the bottom of my heart for taking this journey with me!

Habari Gani! (What’s the news?)

Kujichagulia (Self-Determination)

It’s day 2 of Kwanzaa! For today’s principal, we honor Kujichagulia which is Swahili for Self-Determination.

With Self-Determination we try to to define and name ourselves, as well as to create and speak for ourselves. And that’s exactly what I get to do with taking you all on this Kwanzaa journey with me each year. Joyous Kwanzaa indeed!! ❤️🖤💚

Habari Gani? (What’s the news?)

Ujima (Collective Work & Responsibility)

Joyous Kwanzaa FinFam and friends! On this third day, we honor Ujima, which means Collective Work and Responsibility. In essence, we take the time to build and maintain our community together and make our brothers’ and sisters’ problems our problems and to solve them together. 

How can you practice Ujima today? Are you still using your voice? So much is happening in the world right now. And you can make a difference. We’re all in this together. ❤️🖤💚

Happily enjoying the rest of the year in Fiji. And even though I’m now a day ahead of normal posting schedules, I’ll still be posting for my general time zone at home.

“You are where you are today because you stand on somebody’s shoulders. And wherever you are heading, you cannot get there by yourself. If you stand on the shoulders of others, you have a reciprocal responsibility to live your life so that others may stand on your shoulders. It’s the quid pro quo of life. We exist temporarily through what we take, but we live forever through what we give.” - Vernon Jordan

Habari Gani! (What’s the news?)

Ujamaa (Cooperative Economics)

Joyous Kwanzaa friends! It’s day four of this beautiful holiday, and today we celebrate Ujamaa which means Cooperative Economics. The essence? To build and maintain our own stores, shops, and other businesses and to profit from them together. 

Supporting Black businesses has been around much longer than the recent trends. I’ve found myself practicing this a lot during my time here in Fiji.

Why is it important to shop from Black owned businesses in the first place? In short to close the racial wealth gap from Jim Crow-era practices, strengthening local economies by supporting small businesses, and also to foster job creation. There’s a lot to unpack there but I’ll let you all do your own homework on that 😉 Anywho, thank you for your patience and open minds. I’m so happy you’re on this journey with me! ❤️🖤💚 

That’s aside, none of us can grow without those around us. And The Abalone Merman wouldn’t be where he is today without the help of his friends, and all of your support. So thank you 💚💚💚

“No one should negotiate their dreams. Dreams must be free to flee and fly high. No government, no legislature, has a right to limit your dreams. You should never agree to surrender your dreams.” - Jesse Jackson

Habari Gani! (What’s the news!)

Nia (Purpose)

Happy 5th day of Kwanzaa! Today we celebrate Nia which means Purpose. The goal is to make our collective vocation the building and developing of our community in order to restore our people to their traditional greatness. In other words understanding the need to bring each other up instead of down. 

How can you benefit your community? What are your dreams and goals? Which ones benefit human kind? What puts us here that makes this world a better place? Remember we are all special and have something to offer. Set new goals for the coming year. If we can better ourselves, we can better each other. 

I know I’m here to touch people through art. It’s why I teach, perform, direct, choreograph, and influence on social media. Spreading light to the best of my ability to try and make this world a happier place, while also sharing knowledge along the alway as I grow older and wiser.  Always learning, and always growing. I hope at some point I’ve made you smile, think, and/or be inspired. And I will always continue to do so. ❤️🖤💚

New Zealand, you were absolutely magical and will forever have my heart ✨🩵✨

Fun fact FinFam for those of you newer here. New Zealand is the main inspiration for my mersona (both Merman Maui and The Abalone Merman) and my love for Paua (abalone) and this beautiful culture. I used to to work for Air New Zealand in Los Angeles for a while in my early 20s, and I ever actually made it here. I was finally going to come on a familiarization trip, but left the job right before the planned trip as I had gotten accepted into a competitive college program (the same college I now teach at) and seized the opportunity to attend. 15 years later, I’ve finally made it here! 💚💙💚

Finally making it to New Zealand to start off the year was a dream come true. And since NZ holds special meaning for who Keenon the Abalone Merman is, I figured I’d create something truly special for me. Y’all have been here the whole step of the way on my self love journey. Truthfully the journey sucked… haha. But making it to the other side truly is a beautiful feeling unlike anything I’ve ever felt before. 

Keenon. You’ve come a long way. Despite the many ups and downs you stayed strong and positive, and I’m proud of you. And most importantly, I love you. I can’t wait to see how you carry this love for the rest of your life. Shine bright king. I got your back, and always will 💙🩵💖🩵💙
